                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Why must someone who believes that charm is overpowered have 'charm envy'?<br /><br />I can borrow a level 65 enchanter almost anytime I wish.  I know how to charm in HoH.  Rather than *****ing, I could be utilizing my two computers to rack up XP.<br /><br />I have a level 63 necromancer twink.  I've stayed 63 simply because I felt I should catch up on a few AA's and I don't have access to any 64-65 spells until our three guild necromancer mains are fully equipped spell-wise.  If I wanted to break my bank, I could have Ervil to 65 in a couple of marathon days of PoS hunting, then start offering 200K or so for the charm spell.  I'm sure that in a short time I'd be competing with the rest of the necros for CoD-space.<br /><br />My guild uses charm effectively to make POP and other encounters easier. Hell, last night a handfull of us used charm to take out Seru mini-named mobs in order to finish off a few earrings.  That's not even PoP, yet I directly benefited from the use of charm toward my own quest. (Edit:  I know that charm could be used for things like this before POP came out.  The 'broken' issue in my mind is the scale that PoP extended this to).<br /><br />No, it's not envy.  It's acknowledgement that something is broken.  I would just as swiftly decry any such bug or exploit.  To dismiss my arguments as 'envy' is to commit a logical fallacy.<br /><br />I have given valid, informed situations as my basis. I have refuted the argument that there is undue risk involved with the situation.  I can refute the argument that there are only a few spots available to charm by saying that if there are so few spots, then fixing this issue won't hurt the majority of players.<br /><br />As for Rallos, yes.  Sony tried to design PoP encounters around various different tactical solutions.  Of course they intended for charm to be used.  They didn't anticipate that it would also present inbalances in the XP game.  It did.  It won't be the first time that Sony's intentions fell awry and they had to fix it.  Just because the speedometer on your car goes to 120 doesn't provide a logical argument for increasing the speed limit.  Besides, it's obvious that Sony differentiates between the intended use for charm and that which players have put it to.  The proposed adjustments shouldn't affect the Rallos encounter, and if it turns out that they do, then that issue will be fixed. <br /><br />But they're taking their sweet time about doing it.  It should have been done months ago.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
